{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477875"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:07:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:07:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14906"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14906"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.02,0.09,0.79,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7597"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115001"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7597"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14906"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97007"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"1351"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18594"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48376"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115001"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-day history of sore throat and fever. He has difficulty swallowing but can breathe normally. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears lethargic. His pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. His tonsils are enlarged and inflamed with white patches. His cervical lymph nodes are symmetrically enlarged and tender. His spleen is palpable 2 cm below the left costal margin. Blood tests show a white cell count of 12 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0) with a relative decrease in lymphocytes and atypical forms present on blood film.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peritonsillar abscess","Viral pharyngitis","Group A Streptococcal pharyngitis","Infectious mononucleosis","Acute bacterial tonsillitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis adolescent presents with the hallmark features of infectious mononucleosis: sore throat, fever, fatigue, cervical lymphadenopathy and splenomegaly. Atypical lymphocytes are commonly seen in infectious mononucleosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfectious mononucleosis\u003C/strong\u003E most commonly affects teenagers and young adults. The combination of fever, sore throat and swollen lymph nodes occurs in most cases. An enlarged spleen is found in about half of patients and is a critical finding as it requires avoiding contact sports.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGroup A Streptococcal pharyngitis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause white patches on the tonsils, but does not typically cause an enlarged spleen or produce abnormal lymphocytes. It usually develops more quickly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeritonsillar abscess\u003C/strong\u003E characteristically causes severe one-sided throat pain with difficulty opening the mouth and displacement of the uvula. These distinguishing features are absent here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral pharyngitis\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0from other causes, like adenovirus, generally produces milder symptoms without spleen enlargement or significant lymph node swelling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute bacterial tonsillitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically has a more sudden onset. It does not cause spleen enlargement or produce atypical lymphocytes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment focuses on supportive measures including rest, fluids and pain relief. Contact sports must be avoided for several weeks to prevent splenic injury. Most patients recover fully within 2-4 weeks without specific treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Infectious mononucleosis classically presents with fever, pharyngitis, lymphadenopathy and splenomegaly in adolescents.","Atypical lymphocytes are commonly seen in infectious mononucleosis.","Patients with infectious mononucleosis must avoid contact sports due to risk of splenic rupture."],"references":["Wolford RW, Goyal A, Belgam Syed SY, et al. Pharyngitis. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519550/","Hoover K, Higginbotham K. Epstein-Barr Virus. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559285/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97007"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14906"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97007"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T18:51:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T18:52:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7597"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115001"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id"